.TH "vbin_printf" 9 "vbin_printf" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
vbin_printf \- Parse a format string and place args' binary value in a buffer
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "int" vbin_printf
.BI "(u32 *bin_buf "  ","
.BI "size_t size "  ","
.BI "const char *fmt "  ","
.BI "va_list args "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "bin_buf" 12
The buffer to place args' binary value
.IP "size" 12
The size of the buffer(by words(32bits), not characters)
.IP "fmt" 12
The format string to use
.IP "args" 12
Arguments for the format string
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
The format follows C99 vsnprintf, except n is ignored, and its argument
is skipped.

The return value is the number of words(32bits) which would be generated for
the given input.
.SH "NOTE"
If the return value is greater than \fIsize\fP, the resulting bin_buf is NOT
valid for \fBbstr_printf\fP.
